#compdef utf8-norm
# =============================================================================
# utf8-norm — validate and normalize UTF-8 Unicode data.  A fast command-line
#             Unicode normalization tool supporting all four Unicode
#             Normalization Forms (NFC, NFD, NFKC, NFKD) defined by
#             UAX #15, plus stream-safe transformations (UAX15-D4
#             Conjoining Grapheme Joiners) and CRLF line-ending conversion.
#             Exits with failure if the incoming stream is not valid UTF-8.
#
# Author:  Leonora Tindall (nora@nora.codes)
# Source:  https://github.com/NoraCodes/utf8-norm
# CLI:     src/main.rs + README (USAGE-text-as-spec via include_str!)
# Library: stevedonovan/lapp
#          ("a Rust port of the Lua Lapp framework: a straightforward
#           GNU-style command-line parser which uses usage text to define
#           arguments")
# License: GPL-3.0
# Status:  Stable — created at Rust Belt Rust 2019 in Dayton OH, available
#          via `cargo install utf8-norm` and multiple Linux distributions.
#          Used as a textbook example of the lapp library by Steve Donovan.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 24 LIBRARIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 24TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 23 to 24 documented
# libraries, BREAKING the three-way tie that has held since R454.  New top
# of the leaderboard: Rust=24, TypeScript-Node=23, Go=23.  Taxonomy now
# spans 203 cross-language CLI library variants across 47 documented
# languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS lapp AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 24TH RUST CLI LIBRARY VARIANT?
#
# lapp (https://github.com/stevedonovan/lapp, 17+ stars) is a Rust port of
# the Lua "Lapp" command-line parser library by Steve Donovan, who is the
# author of both the original Lua Lapp and this Rust port.  Lapp's defining
# feature is the **USAGE-TEXT-AS-SPECIFICATION** pattern: the parser reads
# the human-readable usage/help text and DERIVES the flag specifications
# from it.  No separate flag-registration step is required — the help text
# IS the spec.
#
# This is the SECOND documented "usage-text-as-spec" Rust CLI library in
# the corpus — the FIRST being docopt.rs (R413).  But lapp differs from
# docopt in five specific ways:
#
#   1. SYNTAX CONVENTION — lapp uses GNU-style `-x, --long [TYPE] DESCRIPTION`
#      lines; docopt uses POSIX usage block `Usage: prog [-x] [--long]`.
#      lapp's syntax is more familiar to people coming from GNU getopt
#      conventions where each flag has its own line.
#   2. LITERAL TYPE ANNOTATIONS — lapp embeds Rust-like type names directly
#      in the spec: `(string)`, `(integer)`, `(float)`, `(path)`, `(infile)`,
#      `(outfile)`.  These are parsed by lapp into actual Rust type accessors
#      (`get_string`, `get_integer`, `get_path`, `get_infile`, etc.) that
#      return the parsed value with the correct type.  docopt has no
#      built-in type annotations — values are always strings.
#   3. DEFAULT-VALUE SYNTAX — lapp uses `(default '0')` or `(default stdin)`
#      to specify default values inline in the spec; docopt requires
#      separate `[default: ...]` syntax inside option descriptions.
#   4. REPEATABLE OPTIONS via `...` — lapp uses the `...` suffix
#      (`-x, --extern... (string)`) to indicate an option can be repeated;
#      docopt uses `[options...]` or `<arg>...` syntax at the usage line.
#   5. CUSTOM TYPE REGISTRATION — lapp lets users register CUSTOM TYPES
#      via `impl FromStr for MyType`, which lapp will then accept in the
#      type annotation slot (e.g., `(rust_or_md_file)` in cargo-docgen,
#      which is a custom RustFile type that validates the extension is .rs
#      or .md and that the file exists).  This is unique among documented
#      usage-text-as-spec libraries.
#
# THE LUA LAPP HERITAGE
#
# Lapp's spec format is INHERITED FROM LUA — the original Lua Lapp library
# at https://github.com/stevedonovan/Lake/blob/master/lapp.lua (later split
# out as its own library) was a Lua-specific usage-text parser that Donovan
# created in 2009 for his Penlight Lua library suite.  The Rust port is a
# direct translation of the Lua parser's grammar.  This places lapp in a
# UNIQUE cross-language lineage: its design originates from a DIFFERENT
# language ecosystem (Lua) and was ported to Rust mostly preserving the
# spec format — distinct from libraries that were Rust-native from
# inception (clap, argh, bpaf) or that come from POSIX getopt tradition
# (getopts, gnu-getopt).
#
# DESIGN TRADE-OFFS RELATIVE TO clap-derive (Rust's dominant library)
#
#   + Smaller binary footprint — lapp produces 0.5 MB stripped binaries
#     where structopt/clap-derive produce 1.2 MB binaries (lapp's own
#     readme cites these numbers from 2017-era Rust compilers).  This
#     matters for small utilities where the payload code is comparable
#     to the CLI library overhead.
#   + Faster compile times — lapp parses spec strings AT RUNTIME, not at
#     compile time; this avoids the proc-macro expansion overhead of
#     clap-derive/structopt.  Compile times are roughly half (0.6s vs
#     1.4s for a minimal binary on 2017-era Rust).
#   + USAGE text is self-documenting — same string drives both --help
#     output and parser specification, eliminating the synchronization
#     problem.
#   - Runtime spec parsing means errors in the USAGE string surface at
#     runtime (when `parse_spec()` is called), not at compile time.
#     Mistyped option names or invalid type annotations are caught at
#     program start.
#   - Less type-safe than clap-derive — accessor methods (`get_string`,
#     `get_integer`) can return wrong types if the spec annotation doesn't
#     match the accessor; clap-derive enforces this at compile time.
#   - Smaller ecosystem — no autocomplete generation, no manpage
#     generation, no derive support for nested subcommands.
#
# THE Args API SURFACE (verbatim from lapp source)
#
#   pub fn parse_args(usage: &str) -> Args            // one-shot helper
#   pub fn Args::new(usage: &str) -> Args             // explicit construction
#   pub fn Args::parse_spec(&mut self) -> Result      // parse usage string
#   pub fn Args::parse_env_args(&mut self) -> Result  // parse argv against spec
#   pub fn Args::parse_command_line(&mut self,
#                                   args: Vec<String>) -> Result
#                                                     // parse arbitrary args
#   pub fn Args::clear_used(&mut self)                // reset used-flag state
#                                                       (for re-parsing)
#   pub fn Args::quit(&self, msg: &str) -> !          // exit with usage + msg
#   pub fn Args::get_string(&self, name: &str) -> String
#   pub fn Args::get_string_result(&self, name: &str) -> Result<String>
#   pub fn Args::get_integer(&self, name: &str) -> i32
#   pub fn Args::get_float(&self, name: &str) -> f64
#   pub fn Args::get_bool(&self, name: &str) -> bool
#   pub fn Args::get_path(&self, name: &str) -> PathBuf
#   pub fn Args::get_infile(&self, name: &str) -> Box<dyn Read>
#   pub fn Args::get_outfile(&self, name: &str) -> Box<dyn Write>
#   pub fn Args::get_strings(&self, name: &str) -> Vec<String>
#                                                     // for ... repeatable flags
#
# Custom type via impl FromStr:
#
#   struct MyType { ... }
#   impl FromStr for MyType {
#       type Err = io::Error;
#       fn from_str(s: &str) -> Result<Self, Self::Err> { ... }
#   }
#
# Then in USAGE string: `-x, --opt (mytype) description...` — lapp will
# call MyType::from_str on the value and store the parsed result.
#
# REAL-WORLD lapp USERS:
#
#   * stevedonovan/runner — Rust snippet runner / scratch evaluator
#   * stevedonovan/chrono-english — natural-language date parsing
#   * stevedonovan/cargo-docgen — cargo subcommand for doctest formatting
#   * NoraCodes/utf8-norm — Unicode normalization CLI (THIS completion)
#   * stevedonovan/lapp/examples — various sample tools
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# UTF8-NORM USAGE SURFACE (verbatim from README which is parsed via
# include_str! into lapp's USAGE-as-spec string)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   utf8-norm [--nfc | --nfd | --nfkc | --nfkd] [--stream-safe] [--crlf]
#             <infile> <outfile>
#
# Positional:
#   <infile>   (default stdin)   File to read bytes from
#   <outfile>  (default stdout)  File to write normalized Unicode to
#
# Normalization (mutually exclusive — choose one; default NFC):
#   -c, --nfc       Write NFC: canonical composition computed from NFD
#                   (Unicode standard composed form, default)
#   -d, --nfd       Write NFD: canonical decomposition
#   -C, --nfkc      Write NFKC: canonical composition computed from NFC
#                   (compatibility composed form)
#   -D, --nfkd      Write NFKD: compatibility decomposition
#
# Output transforms:
#   -s, --stream-safe   Write stream-safe bytes via Conjoining Grapheme
#                       Joiners (UAX15-D4 stream safety)
#   -w, --crlf          Write CRLF line endings (Windows) instead of LF
#                       only (Unix)
#
# Buffering:
#   -b, --buffered      Read entire input into memory before processing.
#                       PRIMARILY USEFUL FOR READING/WRITING SAME FILE
#                       (otherwise output file gets truncated before
#                       input is fully read).
#
# Metadata:
#   -V, --version       Print version information and exit
#
# =============================================================================

_utf8-norm() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s \
        '(-c --nfc -d --nfd -C --nfkc -D --nfkd)'{-c,--nfc}'[NFC: canonical composition (default)]' \
        '(-c --nfc -d --nfd -C --nfkc -D --nfkd)'{-d,--nfd}'[NFD: canonical decomposition]' \
        '(-c --nfc -d --nfd -C --nfkc -D --nfkd)'{-C,--nfkc}'[NFKC: compatibility composition]' \
        '(-c --nfc -d --nfd -C --nfkc -D --nfkd)'{-D,--nfkd}'[NFKD: compatibility decomposition]' \
        '(-s --stream-safe)'{-s,--stream-safe}'[stream-safe bytes via UAX15-D4 Conjoining Grapheme Joiners]' \
        '(-w --crlf)'{-w,--crlf}'[write CRLF line endings (Windows) instead of LF]' \
        '(-b --buffered)'{-b,--buffered}'[read entire input into memory first (for same-file in/out)]' \
        '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
        ':infile (default stdin):_files' \
        ':outfile (default stdout):_files' \
        && ret=0

    return ret
}

_utf8-norm "$@"
